article.description: Seattle's 76-63 victory over Sacramento extended the Storm's home winning streak to eight games and enabled the Storm to clinch second place in the West.
article.headline: Seattle gains homecourt advantage in first round
article.linkText: Seattle bops Sacramento, clinches No. 2 seed in West
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Storm earned home-court advantage and
perhaps a psychological boost in beating the Sacramento Monarchs on
Thursday night.

Janell Burse scored 17 points, and Lauren Jackson added 14 as
Seattle defeated Sacramento 76-63, clinching second place in the
WNBA's Western Conference.

Seattle (19-14) improved to 13-3 at home -- second best in the
league -- and won its eighth straight home game. More importantly,
the Storm will have home-court advantage in the first round of the
playoffs.

Seattle's opponent will not be determined until Saturday.

"It's kind of nice to control our own destiny, and then did,"
Seattle's Sue Bird said.

Iziane Castro Marques added 13 points and Bird had 12 for the
Storm, who took the season series from Sacramento 2-1. Storm coach
Anne Donovan believes beating the Monarchs twice might have as much
of a benefit as holding home court.

"Having a successful game against Sacramento and having the
season series go our way against them, I think does wonders for our
confidence going into the playoffs," Donovan said. "When you see
that kind of balance on the stat sheet ... that's what you have to
do against Sacramento."

The Monarchs (24-9) came in with a four-game winning streak, but
fell a half-game behind Connecticut for the best record in the
league.

Nicole Powell led Sacramento with 17 points, but Sacramento shot
just 33 percent.

Center Yolanda Griffith was also held in check, making just
3-of-15 shots, and scoring seven points. She had 26 points when the
teams played last Saturday.

"She's a beast. Denying her the ball, keeping her out of the
paint, staying up in her face, all that's tough," Burse said of
defending Griffith. "When she caught it ... I had to not allow her
to have easy turnaround jumpers."

Seattle appeared on its way to an easy victory, scoring a
season-high 49 first-half points, and leading by 15 early in the
second half.

Instead, Sacramento increased the defensive pressure and rattled
the Storm. Seattle scored just 13 points the first 13 minutes of
the half.

With the Monarchs trailing 63-54, Powell made a 3-pointer, and
then three free throws after being fouled on a 3-point attempt.

"Our plan was to cut the lead under 10 by 10 minutes to go and
get it to four or five with five minutes left and we were there,"
Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "In the second half, I was
pleased with my team."

Leading 64-60 with 5:36 remaining, Seattle scored the next 11
points to go up by 15 with 2:30 to go. Jackson had five points in
the run.

"We had opportunities to cut into the lead, but we just
couldn't knock the shots down," Griffith said. "We have to stay
focused and knock those shots down ... especially me."

Unlike their meeting of five days earlier, the Storm took
control early and forced the Monarchs to play from behind. On
Saturday, Sacramento beat Seattle 75-65 after taking a 10-point
first-half lead.

Seattle led 37-24 on a 3-pointer by Bird with 5:22 left in the
half. Sacramento cut the lead to 42-38 with 1:56 to go, but Seattle
scored the final seven points of the half, capped by Bird's
three-point play -- a banked 18-footer -- with less than a second to
go.

"We didn't have our best first half. We weren't as efficient as
we like to be," Whisenant said. "They are tough here."

Seattle's Betty Lennox played in her second game since missing
six straight with a torn ligament in her left wrist.

Sacramento played without reserve guard Kara Lawson, who injured
her left shoulder in the closing seconds of the Monarchs' 76-70 win
over Phoenix on Tuesday.
